<br>
The only unbalancing factor in melees favor at lower lvls is the gear available to twinks and you clearly can't balance the game with twinks in mind without screwing over the people who aren't twinks.  Now if we could just get some lvl restrictions on items so lvl 20s couldn't wield a trak tooth or a blood point...<br>
<br>
Personally my view is if your a necro and you think rogues are overpowered in pvp you are lacking in skills.<br>
<br>
pyrocruor 2000 dmg dmg dot<br>
Cessation 1000dmg debuff dot<br>
vex 1100 lifetap over time.<br>
Ebolt 1100 poison dot<br>
Deflux 310 lifetap 3 second cast<br>
DMF +70 pr and levitate<br>
Scent of Terris fr dr and pr down by 50 in pvp<br>
Splurt 1800 dmg dot<br>
<br>
Here are a few tips...<br>
<br>
Know who your enemies are.<br>
<br>
Watch your zone list for enemies.<br>
<br>
When a known enemy apears in the list use your pet to target him as described above.<br>
<br>
Never hunt at a zone line.<br>
<br>
Try never to hunt anywhere easily accessable to someone at the zone line.<br>
<br>
In a dungeon where the rogue is sneaking through since you can target him from anywhere you can test to see if hes in range from time to time.<br>
<br>
You may want to make a hotkey that goes like...<br>
/pet attack name<br>
/pet back off<br>
/target name of your current pet<br>
/assist<br>
<br>
Then hit it from time to time and try to cast.  If your enemy is sneaking around in a dungeon to reach you he will probably agro a mob when your spell breaks his hide in any high lvl dungeon he will most likely die.<br>
<br>
If no mobs are around or its outdoors he should have your pet on him and dots that he wont be able to dispell without prenerf pumice.<br>
<br>
Even if it doesn't go like this you can shadowstep and work the terain in order to keep from dying to his dmg and meanwhile even if you can't cast much you should be able to get some defluxes off while your pet works on killing the rogue.<br>
<br>
If you get a good shadowstep off you should easily be able to even cast a dot that he wont be able to get rid of without ditching your pet.  Of course the rogue could potentially manage to finish you off (hint try not to show your back)<br>
<br>
Heres another idea shaman dmg shield potion + banshee aura thats a 43 dmg shield at 60<br>
<br>
The rogue is surely not helpless but to describe melees as needing a nerf to 2/3 dmg is ridiculous.<br>
<br>
Strategies for the rogue include dragging the pet off , killing it, then healing up with a velious bp.<br>
Rooting the pet with nets farmed in velious.<br>
If the necro is inclined to cast a lot of pumiable dots and doesn't have a pet up let em then step out of range and pumice em off using up their manna. (yes this requires a dumb necro)<br>
Fighting repeatedly then backing off and healing with mrylo or velious bp<br>
Suprising the necro and wrecking him.<br>
Catching him indoors supposing he doesn't start casting before you come into sight via the pet target thing.<br>
Luring him into somewhere shadowstep wont take you very far and hurting him.<br>
Pre nerf pumice if you've got it.<br>
Training the pet on some npc that hates necros (ok this is kinda cheap)<br>
Running past agro npcs but sneaking letting them run straight to you visible and agro.  The pet will get killed by the mob and the necro will take some dmg before fding or trying to gate.  If you don't want to cause them exp death you can let them gate or fd...or not.<br>
<br>
